**How the schedule works**

This schedule is staffed using 4 crews. There is a crew in each week of
the 4-week cycle. At the end of each week, each crew rotates down to the
next week in the cycle. The crew completing week 4 will rotate up to the
first week of the cycle.

Nights are the last shift of the day. This means that as you look down,
for example, on Friday, of the 3 shifts that show up that day, the night
shift is the first, working from 11:00 pm Friday night until 7:00 am on
Saturday.

There are three notable things about this schedule.

1.  The schedule rotates so every time you come back from a break you
    are on a different shift.

2.  When you return from a break, you will work 7 days in a row.

3.  Once every 4 weeks, there is a 4-day weekend. In the schedule above,
    that weekend begins at 3:00 pm on Friday of week 1 and ends at 11:00
    pm on Wednesday of week 2.

**[24/7 Option #2]{.underline}**: The Dupont 12-hour schedule

![](media/image3.emf)

> N12: 12-hour night shift (6:30 pm to 6:30 am)
>
> D12: 12-hour day shift (6:30 am to 6:30 pm)

**How the schedule works**

This schedule is staffed using 4 crews. There is a crew in each week of
the 4-week cycle. At the end of each week, each crew rotates down to the
next week in the cycle. The crew completing week 4 will rotate up to the
first week of the cycle.

Nights are the last shift of the day. This means that as you look down,
for example, on Tuesday, of the 2 shifts that show up that day, the
night shift is the last. A night shift shown on Tuesday will start
Tuesday night and end Wednesday morning.

Working through a 4-week cycle:

**Week 1**: You work from 6:30 am until 6:30 pm on Monday -- Thursday.
After you get off Thursday evening, you're off on Friday, Saturday, and
Sunday before rotating down to week 2.

**Week 2:** You are off on Monday through Thursday, returning to work on
Friday night a 6:30 pm. You get off your Friday night shift at 6:30 am
on Saturday. You then work a Saturday night and a Sunday night shift
before rotating down to week 3.

**Week 3:** You work Monday night from 6:30 pm until 6:30 am on Tuesday.
You are then off on the rest of Tuesday, Wednesday and Thursday. You
return to work at 6:30 am on Friday and work until 6:30 pm. You do this
again on Saturday and Sunday before rotating down to week 4.

**Week 4:** You are off on Monday, returning to work at 6:30 pm on
Tuesday. You get off the Tuesday night shift at 6:30 am on Wednesday.
You then work a Wednesday and a Thursday night shift with the last shift
ending at 6:30 am on Friday. You are then off for the rest of Friday,
Saturday, and Sunday before rotating up to week 1.

**Questions and Answers**

**[Question #1:]{.underline}** Why are we looking at 24/7 12-hour
schedule?

**[Answer #1:]{.underline}** The workforce has been indicating a desire
for a new schedule for quite some time. We are looking at alternatives
to see if this is something the majority of our employees want to try
out.

**[Question #2:]{.underline}** Why would anyone want a 12-hour schedule?

**[Answer #2:]{.underline}** While the reasons vary, they can be summed
up in 3 words: "More days off."

The current 24/7 schedule has 273 scheduled days of work per year. That
is before any unscheduled overtime. The 12-hour option has 182 scheduled
days of work per year before any unscheduled overtime. Both schedules
have access to unscheduled overtime so that additional income should be
considered the same regardless of the schedule.

**[Question #3]{.underline}**: What are our options?

**[Answer #3:]{.underline}** For those currently working the 8-hour,
24/7 schedule the choices are:

1.  Keep the current schedule

2.  Try the 12-hour, rotating 24/7 schedule known as the Dupont

**[Question #4:]{.underline}** How will the new schedule affect my pay.

**[Answer #4:]{.underline}** The current schedule averages 42 hours of
work per week and 43 hours of pay per week (before unscheduled
overtime). The Dupont schedule averages 42 hours of work per week and 44
hours of pay per week (before any unscheduled overtime). [See Appendix A
for the calculations.]{.underline}

**[Question #5:]{.underline}** How will the new schedule be chosen?

**[Answer #5:]{.underline}** The last page of this document is a
Preference Form. On that page, you will indicate your preference for a
24/7 schedule. You will turn your completed form into the union hall. If
the majority want to try the Dupont schedule, it will be implemented in
early April 2024.

**[Question #6]{.underline}**: How will overtime be paid on the 12-hour
schedule.

**[Answer #6:]{.underline}** On the 12-hour schedule, overtime will be
paid at time and one-half for all hours worked in excess of 40 hours in
a week and in excess of 12 hours in a day.

**[Question #7]{.underline}**: If we choose the new schedule, will it be
for a trial period?

**[Answer #7:]{.underline}** Yes. A new schedule, if chosen, will be in
place from April 2024 until April 2025. After that time, if no action is
taken to make the schedule permanent, you will automatically return to
your current schedule.

If, at any time during the trial, the company finds that absentee
coverage is not working or the schedule becomes a safety or productivity
concern, the schedule will revert back to the current schedule with 30
days' notice. If the union wants to stop the trial early, they can do so
with 30 days notice if two-thirds of the workforce indicates they want
to do so.

**[Question #8:]{.underline}** What will the hours be for the 12-hour
shifts?

**[Answer #8:]{.underline}** The 12-hour Day shift will go from 6:30 am
until 6:30 pm. The 12-hour Night shift will go from 6:30 pm until 6:30
am the following morning.

**[Question #9:]{.underline}** How will vacations work?

**[Answer #9:]{.underline}** On the 12-hour schedule, vacation will be
taken and paid in hours. If you miss a 12-hour shift, you will be paid
for 12 hours and 12 hours will be charged to your account. On 12-hour
schedules, it is often seen as beneficial to take off a "block" of days.
A "block" is defined as a group of consecutive days of work that are
proceeded and followed by a group of days off. If you choose to take a
"block" off, you will not be subjected to mandatory overtime during the
week that contains the majority of your vacation time. For example, if
you take vacation on the 4 night shifts starting on Friday of week 2 and
ending on Monday of week 3, your days off in week 2 will not be
subjected to mandatory overtime.

Vacation pay is currently either 2% of your earnings from the previous
year or 44 pay hours, whichever is greater. This is based on the idea
that a typical week of vacation is equivalent to 40 hours of vacation.
[See Appendix B for Vacation Pay calculations]{.underline}.

[Calculating the Percent Method]{.underline}

To convert to hours, you would get 2% divided by 40 hours for each hour.

.02/40 = .0005 or .05% per hour.

So, if you take 48 hours off, you would get 48 times .05% which comes to
2.4%. If you take 36 hours off, you would get 36 time .05% which comes
to 1.8%. Taking 48 hours gets you more money but uses up your vacation
faster.

[Calculating the 44 pay hours method]{.underline}

Each hour is paid at 44/40 or 10% extra per hour. So, missing 48 hours
will give you 48 plus 4.8 hours of pay or 52.8 pay hours. Missing 36
hours will give you 36 plus 3.6 hours of pay or 39.6 pay hours.

**[Question #10:]{.underline}** How will holidays work?

**[Answer #10:]{.underline}** We currently recognized 14 holidays a
year, seven scheduled holidays and 7 floating holidays. On the 12-hour
schedule, there will be a total of 12 holidays, seven scheduled and 5
floating holidays. You will continue to get 8 hours of Holiday Pay for
each scheduled holiday but you will get 12 hours of pay for each
floating holiday. You will continue to be paid at time and one-half for
all hours worked on a holiday. This is in addition to Holiday Pay. [See
Appendix C for pay calculations related to holidays]{.underline}.

Southern Swing: Time off with 7 floating holidays: 7 times 8 hours = 56
hours

> Pay for 7 floating holidays: 7 times 8 hours = 56 pay hours

Dupont: Time off with 5 floating holidays: 5 times 12 hours = 60 hours

> Pay for 5 floating holidays: 5 times 12 hours = 60 hours

