**[Question #12:]{.underline}** Will there be a Stand-by system for the
12-hour schedule?

**[Answer #12:]{.underline}** Covering short-notice absences on a
12-hour schedule is different than doing so on an 8-hour schedule.
Currently, if someone doesn't show up for work at the last minute, the
person in that position will stay over. This is not something that
should routinely happen on 12-hour shifts.

When people first here this, it's not unusual to hear "I knew there was
catch! Now we have to come in on our days off so why bother with 12-hour
shifts?"

The math actually clarifies this. If you stay on your current schedule,
you have 91 days off per year. However, you don't have to come in on
those days off. You come in early or stay late. So, for example, if you
provide 120 hours of absentee coverage during a year, you will keep your
91 days off but 30 of your workdays will have been converted to 12-hour
shifts.

On the other hand, on a 12-hour schedule, you have 182 days off per
year. If you provide 120 hours of coverage on that schedule, you will
lose 10 of your days off so you will end up with only 172 days off per
year. This is 81 more days off that your current schedule with the same
amount of unscheduled overtime.

Most absentee coverage for things like vacation, can be scheduled in
advance. Overtime can be posted and distributed in accordance with the
current contract language, and no one needs to worry about last minute
coverage\...unless, someone calls off at the last minute.

Last minute coverage means that some will have to come in on their day
off when they weren't expecting to.

To be clear, this is in reference to a position that MUST BE FILLED for
the facility to operate safely. Not only must it be filled, there is
also no one available on that shift to cover it.

Telephone calls or text messages will need to be used to find someone
that can come in. If no one comes in, the facility must either shut down
or operate with short staffing.

Since neither of these options is acceptable, companies rely on a
standby system. This is a policy in which there is always someone
assigned to answer the phone and come in for a short period of time
around shift changes. [See Appendix D for what a system may look
like]{.underline}.

The company can design a system that guarantees coverage, or the union
can. In either case, coverage must be guaranteed, or the schedule will
revert to the current 8-hour pattern. Putting in a schedule that causes
occasional stoppages is in no one's best interest.

Shiftwork Solutions has found that shift workers step up to the plate
and answer their phones when it is understood that failure to do so will
cause the 12-hour schedule to go away.

However, old habits are hard to break. On 8-hour schedules, there are
not a lot of days off so people may have historically avoided answering
the call when it comes in. This needs to change on 12-hour shifts.

Shiftwork Solutions recommends a 3-Flag System. In this system, there is
no standby program. Instead, the company agrees that it will allow two
failures of a voluntary system before either (1) reverting to the old
8-hour schedule or (b) putting in a mandatory standby system.

Each failure is a Flag.

Flag 1: There was a short notice absence, and no one would come in to
fill it. Everyone is notified that this first flag has occurred.

Flag 2: There was a short notice absence, and no one would come in to
fill it. Everyone is notified that this second flag has occurred.

Flag 3: There was a short notice absence, and no one would come in to
fill it. Either the old 8-hour schedule is implemented, or a mandatory
standby system is put in place.

This gives the workforce the ability to avoid a standby system. No one
wants to implement such a system but if no one comes in to cover short
notice absences, then such a system is the only way to make the 12-hour
schedule work.

