**Appendix E -- Unscheduled Overtime and Days Off**

On the Southern Swing, overtime is worked by extending a regularly
scheduled shift. On a 12-hour schedule, overtime is worked on a day off.

Let's assume that you work no double shifts, no 16's, on the Southern
Swing. As you work more and more overtime, more and more of your 8-hour
shifts become 12-hour shifts. For example, if you average 6 hours of
overtime a week for a year, you will end up having worked 195 8-hour
shifts and 78 12-hour shifts. However, since we don't work overtime on a
day off, you will always have 91 days off regardless of how much
overtime you work.

On a 12-hour schedule, the more overtime you work, the fewer days off
you have. For example, you start with 182 days off but, if you work an
average of 6 hours of overtime a week for a year, you will end up
working 208 12-hour shifts and having 156 days off.

